This game does have insane potential. The basic gameplay loop is really engaging and monkey minion mechanic is great. However quickly after starting the game I started to see major flaws that just kept piling onto each other.

The game is painfully slow. The run speed is pathetic considering the amount of exploring you have to do. You can go faster by rolling, but that takes stamina, which runs out incredibly fast so you have to wait every 5 seconds to be able to roll again. Crafting of some items takes insane amount of time, even with max level crafting monkeys and that's on top of gathering resources. It took me at least an HOUR to make my first 5x4 tile wooden house with the help of my first monkey.

When stamina depletes completely, you get a screen effect that would be fine from time to time, but it gets annoying fast because you see it every 5 seconds if you try to roll to go faster. Even worse, stamina regens SLOWER if you don't use it up completely, so you will be spamming roll till you're out just to roll again faster. This rewards mindlessly roll-spamming and makes you endure the screen effects is you want to any sort of fast.

Monkey minions are a great concept, but executed in the most simplistic way it can, which can lead to annoyances. Monkeys choose chests to put things in seemingly at random sometimes, so say bye to neatly organized storage. If there was a solid way to influence where they put things, then it had to be buried in text tutorials because I sure didn't figure it out during gameplay. You can't tell them to craft only a certain amount, so if you make a monkey chain of "bring-craft-take back to chest", they WILL end up wasting resources by crafting too much if you leave them without strict supervision. They will also use tools till they break, wasting MORE resources to craft them new ones instead of repairing, unless you micromanage them like crazy to take tools from them for repairs at the right time. If you tell a monkey to plant seeds, it won't have any consideration for what to plant where either, so no efficient automated farm either.

Resources are overabundant to a point of clogging your inventory in seconds, but amount to so little when you'll start crafting. 6 pebbles for a stone chunk, 2 stone chunks and one mud for a stone slab, 3 stone slabs and 3 mud for a stone wall. 36 pebbles and 6 mud for just ONE stone wall. More than one third of a stack for just ONE tile of wall placed.

Let's have a list of flaws that don't have whole paragraphs worth of commentary before I get to another big one:
-animal taming seems pointless since you can easily just go and kill things for loot without the need to tame, transport and craft breeding feeds;
-hunger feels pointless because food is overabundant to a point of meat and fruit items only clogging your inventory and having to be constantly discarded to make space for more important things;
-raids are a pointless annoyance. The game advises you to build up defenses, but that only makes the raid bigger, so the best defense against them is just going out of the base so no more than three enemies spawn. With teleporters you can also go to an easier island to oneshot them on top of it in later game;
-burning in volcanic biomes and insect swarm in swamp biome debuffs literally don't do anything other than a screen effect and having your character constantly talk in how much pain they are in despite no loss of health nor stamina. Might be a bug, but that's how it was for all of the time of my playthrough, so wasn't patched fast either;
-traders and their fetchquests are boring and a pure grind and rng, so is finding the lore entries;
-bosses are just normal enemies but slightly bigger with more hp;

Now, the last thing that completely ruins this game - progression and balancing. Or rather lack of either. The feel I got was that game expects you to go out and explore islands one by one and move your base from island to island, going up the tiers of buildings and equipment till you reach the finial island and beaten every temple. However that was not my experience at all as the game doesn't do anything to enforce that progression path, and it resulted for balance to completely vanish for me.
I stayed on the starting island without venturing out because there was no push for it. I kept (painfully slowly) building up my base till I was stone tier because I liked the looks and the game kept telling me to build up my defenses, so I did. However I wanted to craft things that needed metal that just wasn't on the starting island and that was what finally pushed me to get on a raft and (painfully slowly) start swimming out.
First island I landed on was the final, hardest one. I thought that harder island = more resources, so I went out to explore and found out that this island had no iron on it, but gold I couldn't mine. I could kill that sparkly fox though, so I (painfully slowly with my dingy bone clubs) did. It exploded into resources, gold among them. I went around, killed a few more foxes, sailed back home when I had a good chunk of stuff that I couldn't do anything with yet. I found the second island after that and got myself iron, but since I had gold from the foxes at that point, I managed to immediately jump over the tier of metal sword and made the gold one right after unlocking. I've barely explored anything past the first island at that point and I've already had an endgame sword in my hands. Progression went out the window at that point cause combat stopped being any challenge and I killed everything effortlessly even though I didn't even bring monkeys anywhere, leaving them to work at the base. Temples were a joke because I demolished enemies.
So after getting the gold sword, the game turned into "run a lot" and "grind resources". Trinkets were useless because I've already beaten everything. Trader quests were a chore since they were either boring fetchquets, or asked me to do redundant things like building a straw house when I had a fully decked stone tier base.

All of those flaws are sadly decorated with a bitter cherry on top that is a disappointing lack of content. Every island has only two mini dungeons and after the first island and breaking balance and progression, I didn't even explore them because I had no need for any loot that could've been in them. That made the islands not worth exploring cause there wasn't anything on them save for loot corpses that had useless sellable trinkets that I kept having to throw out (you can make more money and faster by farming resources and selling those). There is an underwhelming amount of enemy types, most of them are reskins with buffed stats, like three types of boar or big cat that are exactly the same same for hp, damage and sprite. Like I said before, there aren't even bosses, just bigger, beefier versions of normal animal enemies with the same behavior. All went down in 10 seconds or less thanks for my gamebreaking sharpened gold sword. There are barely any decorative things to build with so you can't even make anything pretty.

Overall, this is a game that managed to keep me engaged, but only because I'm a very specific type of person that found it an interesting experience to analyze and think how it could've been done better. It feels like an early access game, a proof of concept, a foundation upon which a better game should only start being built. It by any means doesn't feel like a full product. If you're like me and can get something out of a game that's such an unrealized potential, then get it when it'll be like 70-80% off, no more. Otherwise it sadly isn't worth price nor time, especially since it's not being updated anymore as devs left it to work on something else instead of expanding and polishing what they have done here.
